Visualizing Geographic Data with Python¶

It is a general truth that simple data visualizations can provide powerful insights that would otherwise be unobvious upon examining the underlying data itself. This is double true, in fact, with respect to geographic data. For millenia, cartographers have studied how to make maps more accurate, detailed, and expressive, with the goal of providing a structured way to reason about the world around us. It is one thing to be told about some features of a location; it is another thing entirely to be shown exactly what those features look like.

Now in the 21st century, the same need to visualize geographic information remains. Unlike before, however, we now have a much more powerful tool for generating useful, accurate maps: the computer. Indeed, with the help of modern-day algorithmic and graphical processing, we are able to build maps much more easily than, say, an 8th century Dutch mapmaker. The goal of this article is to teach you how to put that power to good use.

Welcome to the Big Apple!¶

To motivate our expedition into geographic visualization, we'll take a look at a city that is extremely rich in history and culture (and, crucially, datasets): New York, New York! You see, New York is a city of extremes. It has more billionaires than any other city on earth, but also has thousands of homeless people on the streets. It is among the world's most diverse cities, but it also features highly segregated, racially homogenous neighborhoods. It would be easy to simply tell you about these things, but why don't we take it a step further and really visualize them?

Luckily for us, the city has compiled a great dataset concerning these very topics. It's available here from the official data.gov website. I downloaded the dataset in the available CSV format.

Before diving into the code, we'll import some libraries that will help us with our analysis. If any of these libraries is missing on your computer, you can install it using the pip package intaller.

In [1]:
import csv
import pandas as pd
import folium
import json

As we can see, the dataset includes various demographic information for each ZIP code in the city. There are 236 ZIP codes just within New York City itself, so this offers us a reasonable level of granularity for examining differences between different areas.

In order to separate the different ZIP codes on the map that we're building, we'll need a way to represent the shapes of their borders. This can be achieved through geojson files, which define the polygons representing the borders of geographical features. This would take quite a while to build by hand, but luckily someone else has already built such a file which can be found in this GitHub repository. We'll first overlay the shapes of these ZIP codes onto a map of New York in order to get a feel for what they look like.

In [3]:
geo_file = 'nyc-zip-codes.geojson'

# Build base map of NYC
nyc_map = folium.Map(location=[40.7128, -74.0060], zoom_start=10)

# Overlay coloring based on geojson file
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=geo_file,
    fill_opacity=0.5,
).add_to(nyc_map)

nyc_map
Out[3]:

That's a lot of ZIP codes! The folium map here is completely interactive, with zooming and panning available right in your web browser. Pretty cool, right?

Next, we need to associate each ZIP code in our dataset with a ZIP code in the geojson file. In order to make sure that we don't run into any issues with that, we'll first filter the geojson to include only the ZIP codes that exist in our dataset. We'll store that as a new file, and use that file to build our maps.

In [4]:
original_file = open('nyc-zip-codes.geojson')
original_json = json.load(original_file)

# Store the dataset ZIP codes as a set for easy lookups
dataset_zip_codes = set((nyc_stats_df['JURISDICTION NAME']))

matching_zip_codes = list()

# Check each feature in the JSON object
for feature in original_json['features']:
    # Convert ZIP codes from strings to integers
    feature['properties']['postalCode'] = int(feature['properties']['postalCode'])
    
    # If the current feature's ZIP code exists in the dataset, add it to the matching list 
    if(feature['properties']['postalCode'] in dataset_zip_codes):
        matching_zip_codes.append(feature)

# Build a new JSON object with our matching ZIP codes
new_json = dict.fromkeys(['type', 'features'])
new_json['type'] = 'FeatureCollection'
new_json['features'] = matching_zip_codes

# Write the results to a new file
output_file = open('filtered-nyc-zip-codes.geojson', 'w')
output_file.write(json.dumps(new_json, indent=4))

# Use this new file as our geojson file for building maps
geo_file = 'filtered-nyc-zip-codes.geojson'

Show me the data!¶

Now that we've filtered the ZIP codes, we're finally ready to start visualizing! Using the folium library's choropleth method, we can build interactive maps which use our geojson polygons as locational borders and any numerical feature as the basis for coloring.

We'll begin by taking a look at a measure of income inequality. The dataset includes a great proxy for this: the percentage of each ZIP code that receives public assistance. Naturally, we can expect that areas that require more public assistance per capita have higher densities of poverty.

In [5]:
# Build base map of NYC
public_assistance_map = folium.Map(location=[40.7128, -74.0060], zoom_start=10)

# Overlay coloring based on dataset
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=geo_file,
    data=nyc_stats_df,
    fill_opacity=0.7,
    line_opacity=0.2,
    # Geojson property to use for separating objects
    key_on='feature.properties.postalCode', 
    # The first column is associated with the geojson property, 
    # the second column is our metric to display
    columns=['JURISDICTION NAME', 'PERCENT RECEIVES PUBLIC ASSISTANCE'],
    fill_color='YlGnBu',
    legend_name='Proportion of Residents Receiving Public Assistance'
).add_to(public_assistance_map)

public_assistance_map
Out[5]:

As we can see here, there's a huge amount of income inequality in the city. Many ZIP codes have almost no residents receiving public assitance, while there are pockets of the city where almost all residents do. For those who are familiar with New York, we can also see clear differences between each borough of the city. The Bronx features quite a high proportion of residents requiring public assitance; Queens and Staten Island feature almost none; and Manhattan and Brooklyn appear to be a mix of both. Of course, I could have simply told you these things up front, but having a clear picture in front of us allows us to see exactly how these geographic distributions actually look.

Wow, that was easy! With just a few lines of code, we've obtained the power to visualize any metric we want across the city (as long as we have the data for it). We're now free to pick any column of our dataset and throw it onto the map to see how the numbers translate into reality.

Next, let's take a look at some information concerning racial distribution. We'll build the map the exact same way as before, but this time we'll use "Percent Black Non Hispanic" as our metric.

In [6]:
# Build base map of NYC
black_residents_map = folium.Map(location=[40.7128, -74.0060], zoom_start=10)

# Overlay coloring based on dataset
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=geo_file,
    data=nyc_stats_df,
    fill_opacity=0.7,
    line_opacity=0.2,
    # Geojson property to use for separating objects
    key_on='feature.properties.postalCode', 
    # The first column is associated with the geojson property, 
    # the second column is our metric to display
    columns=['JURISDICTION NAME', 'PERCENT BLACK NON HISPANIC'],
    fill_color='YlGnBu',
    legend_name='Proportion of Black Residents'
).add_to(black_residents_map)

black_residents_map
Out[6]:

Wait a minute... this looks very similar to our previous map! The similarity between these maps clearly illustrates a strong correlation between the proportion of an area's residents who are Black, and the proportion of an area's residents who require public assistance (our proxy for poverty).

To demonstrate the point further, we'll contrast these maps with a map of "Percent Asian Non Hispanic."

In [7]:
# Build base map of NYC
asian_residents_map = folium.Map(location=[40.7128, -74.0060], zoom_start=10)

# Overlay coloring based on dataset
folium.Choropleth(
    geo_data=geo_file,
    data=nyc_stats_df,
    fill_opacity=0.7,
    line_opacity=0.2,
    # Geojson property to use for separating objects
    key_on='feature.properties.postalCode', 
    # The first column is associated with the geojson property, 
    # the second column is our metric to display
    columns=['JURISDICTION NAME', 'PERCENT ASIAN NON HISPANIC'],
    fill_color='YlGnBu',
    legend_name='Proportion of Asian Residents'
).add_to(asian_residents_map)

asian_residents_map
Out[7]:

As we can see, the distribution of Asian residents in the city looks completely different. This suggests that a considerable degree of racial and economic segregration exists in the city today. Of course, this demonstrates only correlations, not any sort of casuation. We'd have to dig deeper to examine explanatory causes of this discrepancy, but our visualizations have provided a solid starting point for interesting features to examine.

Conclusion¶

In a relatively short period of time, we've gone from a large, raw dataset to several vivid, interactive maps. This required only a bit of astute data cleansing and analysis on our part.

Sure, we could have taken a look at the raw data and come to similiar conclusions ourselves. But the power of visualization here is clear it allows us to quickly showcase exactly the information we're interested in, in a way that's easily accessible by people from all backgrounds.

It's important to remember that a key goal of data science is to use data in order to draw conclusions about the real world. Sure, advanced statistics and machine learning techniques are invaluable for drawing such conclusions, but these findings wouldn't mean much without a simple way of communicating them to others. My hope is that I've been able to demonstrate the power that even relatively simple techniques can have for extracting key insights from our data.
